@Barry Ancona 

I heard it on the o-vine.

Nobody did it.

@Sam Corbin 

Don't be too hard on yourself. I'm surprised neither the constructor not the editors thought to explicitly link these two, mirror-symmetrical entries to the puzzle. It would have added to the fun.

Or maybe they're Easter eggs for us to find.

@Jody 

I had that thought many years ago when a similar clue appeared in a puzzle. While it is true that there is no B St. in the center of Washington, where all the famous buildings and monuments are, if you cross the Anacostia River into eastern DC, there is indeed a B St.  And even an A St.:

<a href="https://www.google.com/maps/@38.8878844,-76.9563975,17.42z?entry=ttu" target="_blank">https://www.google.com/maps/@38.8878844,-76.9563975,17.42z?entry=ttu</a>

@Michael Weiland

Not always. 

There’s a rare genus called Parnassian, that pupates in a cocoon. These butterflies live in the Pacific Northwest, in Siberia, and as far away as North Korea and the northern islands of Japan.

@Steven M. 
If only Sting could have snuck POLYPHEMUS into Wrapped Around Your Finger. 

<a href="https://youtu.be/svWINSRhQU0?si=E-CjNGWQLm6L_fsQ" target="_blank">https://youtu.be/svWINSRhQU0?si=E-CjNGWQLm6L_fsQ</a>

@Bill 
Pierre Grimal reminded me that the Polyphemus' father was the Olympian* Poseidon, his mother the nymph Thooas; so clearly the gene for cyclopism was passed down on the X-chromosome.




*Poseidon kept a pied-à-terre on Olympus, for tax purposes, although he spent most of his time at his beach-house.

@R2hule 
Well, yes, although the letterform of the Roman H was taken from that of the Eta, as well as the Greek signs for smooth- and ("H"-sounded) rough-breathing, the Eta chopped in half.




Aspirate Emus.

@Michael 

Wasn't it just a while ago that we learned here that a watermelon is a prolate spheroid?

(Polar axis longer than equatorial axis.)

@John Dietsch 
By contrast, there's John Goodman's portrayal of Polyphemos in *O Brother, where art Thou?*, as the eye-patch-wearing, chicken-eating Bible salesman "Big Dan" Teague. Later we find out he's also a member of the KKK.




O Emu, where art thou?

@Bonnie 

I was about to correct you on Ikea, which started in Sweden, but I was surprised to learn that its headquarters are in the Netherlands (at least for legal reasons). 

I hope your recovery goes well. Try not to overdo it.

@ad absurdum

Jocular and ocular. Aye, I like it.


























in the kingdom of the blind, the one-eyed emu is a pain in the... eyes?

@Bonnie 
I agree on the single unchecked square, it was a real missed opportunity. Xword info has a whole collection of unchecked square puzzles, including those with just a single such square. There was one remarkable puzzle 8/29/2013 in which a single unchecked square in the very center of the grid was to be filled in as the rebus EYE (or just E of course). At the completion of the puzzle that square was replaced by a graphic of an eyeball. Of course that was a Thursday, which with such a trick this puzzle likely also would be, See:

<a href="https://tinyurl.com/sz3rvnsm" target="_blank">https://tinyurl.com/sz3rvnsm</a>

@Frances

What Lynn said. And, even if the couple being married isn't actually sitting in the pews, eloping is essentially eschewing the pews because they're choosing a method and ceremony where they're not inviting folks— family, friends, what have you— to fill those pews. They're skipping the pews-filled ceremony.

And I'm Jewish, and have never heard the word 'pews' used for the seats in a synagogue but it still felt like a completely kosher clue/answer to me.

@CaptainQuahog Thanks, but references to the beautiful silk moth appear already in earlier posts. I tend to post first and read other comments later.

Even more lovely, perhaps, than Antheraea polyphemus is Actias luna. Haven't seen either species in the last few years ...

<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Luna_moth" target="_blank">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Luna_moth</a>

@Capital Resident 

There is an explanation of this earlier in the comments.

Something about a portion of B street still existing east of something something...   East DC maybe.

@Capital Resident 

Huh?

I read:"Starting at the US Capitol, the first east-west streets north and south of the Capitol are named A ST, the second east-west streets north and south of the Capitol are named B ST, the third C ST, and so on. The street names run through to Y with the letters J, X, and Z skipped."

@Becca 
I absolutely love your commentary in general and this whole post in particular. But I think the rest of your entire first paragraph argues against your first line about, “It may be about time for me to at last read ‘The Iliad’ and the 
‘Odyssey’ “. It seems you understand the relevant parts of these works and there is so much out there to read, and for so many of us, so little time to do so.  IMHO, reading these original works could drop a little on the priority list. Commenters in this forum often recommend literary works which I often then look up and order on iBooks. I’m happy with my e-library, but I am way behind on keeping up with it.

@Hardroch @Becca
I've looked at life from both sides now.
I don't think I ever read the iliad or the odyssey, and I feel that I should. but the days grow short when we reach September, and I will never read all the things I want to.
